🔹 Problem: Encode and Decode Strings

Design two functions:
encode(vector<string>) → string
decode(string) → vector<string>

👉 The encoding should allow you to uniquely reconstruct the original list.

🧠 1. Brute Force Approach (Simple Delimiter)
💡 Idea:

Join strings using a delimiter like # or |

✅ Code:
string encode(vector<string>& strs) {
    string res = "";
    for(string s : strs) {
        res += s + "#";
    }
    return res;
}

vector<string> decode(string s) {
    vector<string> result;
    string temp = "";

    for(char c : s) {
        if(c == '#') {
            result.push_back(temp);
            temp = "";
        } else {
            temp += c;
        }
    }
    return result;
}

❌ Cons (VERY IMPORTANT):

❌ Breaks if string contains #

["ab#c"] → ambiguous
❌ Cannot distinguish actual delimiter vs content
❌ Not reliable → invalid solution in interviews

📌 When to use:
Only as a starting idea (then reject it yourself)

⚡ 2. Better Approach (Escape Character)

💡 Idea:
Use delimiter but escape it inside strings

Example:
"#" → "\#"

❌ Cons:
Complex to implement correctly
Multiple edge cases (escaping \, nested escapes)
Easy to make mistakes in interview

📌 When to use:
Rarely preferred
Only if interviewer pushes for delimiter-based solution

🚀 3. Optimal Approach (Length Prefix Encoding) ✅
💡 Idea:
Store:
length + '#' + string

👉 Example:

["abc","de"] → "3#abc2#de"

✅ Code:
string encode(vector<string>& strs) {
    string res = "";

    for(string s : strs) {
        res += to_string(s.size()) + "#" + s;
    }

    return res;
}

vector<string> decode(string s) {
    vector<string> result;
    int i = 0;

    while(i < s.size()) {
        int j = i;

        // find '#'
        while(s[j] != '#') j++;

        int len = stoi(s.substr(i, j - i));
        j++; // move past '#'

        string word = s.substr(j, len);
        result.push_back(word);

        i = j + len;
    }

    return result;
}

⏱ Complexity:
Time: O(n)
Space: O(n)

❌ Cons:
Slightly more logic to implement
Need careful parsing (index handling)

✅ Why this is BEST:
Works with any characters (including #, spaces, symbols)
No ambiguity
Industry-standard approach
